<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-009-163 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 503 654</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 20 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australia is test site for new NCR ATMs. (automated tellermachines)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   NCR Corp. (Management).andO;Ticker:    NCR.andO;Topic:     BankingTestingAutomated teller machinesAustralia.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Australia Is Test Site For New NCR ATMs 11/20/91 MELBOURNE, AUSTRALIA, 1991NOV 20 (NB) -- NCR, the world's largest supplier of automatic teller machines(ATMs), has tested its latest models in Australia prior to a general release.andO;NCR is now the computer division of ATandamp;T.andM;The new NCR ATMs are the 56xx family, and are based on personal computersrunning the OS/2 operating system.andP;  While ATMs are inherently reliable (asthey must function without human operators) these latest machines are said tobe two or three times as dependable as the previous model.andP;  That gives theman estimated failure rate (when a service person must be called) of aroundonce per 50,000 transactions, or five months of use.andM;The machines have VGA (video graphics array) screens, and more capabilitythan previous models, including statement printing and passbook transactions.andO;Note capacity remains at 10,000 as this appears the best compromise of sizeand likely usage.andM;The machines not only have advanced diagnostics built in, but are able toauto-correct many failures, obviating the need for a service call.andP;  And evenwhen a call is needed, the machine will, in most cases, have contacted theservice center and booked the parts or assemblies needed by the serviceperson.andM;NCR maintains that ATMs are moving away from the cash dispenser role, andwill become the main interface between bank and customer in many cases.andO;Reasons given are better access, lower cost, fewer arguments, and a fullrange of services.andM;(Paul Zucker/19911120)</TEXT></DOC>